<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-069-133 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 260 939</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Sept 1991 v20 n11 p170(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Putting the 'multi' into multivendor support. (EOT) (Novell Inc.'sTechnical Support Alliance) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kaplan, Jeffrey M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Novell Inc's Technical Support Alliance may offer users ofmultivendor systems some relief from the problems of distributeddata processing using products from different vendors.andP;  Someanalysts believe that the TSA may prove more successful thanprevious networking alliances because it recognizes thatmultivendor computing environments involve more than one company.andO;Single-source support from the major equipment manufacturers hasbeen in place for some time.andP;  Critics of these programs, where thevendor repairs other manufacturers equipment, say that they arereally just a way for the major vendors to maintain proprietarycontrol of the customer account.andP;  The TSA on the other hand isattempting to encourage communication between the differentmembers of the alliance.andP;  Consequently, each member has adesignated employee who can be called by another member to giveadvice when needed.andP;  Additionally, the members of TSA arecross-training their support staff in other vendor's products, andmaking their support organizations, such as bulletin boardsystems, available to each other.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Novell Inc. (Management).andO;Topic:     Support ServicesComputer industryTrade and professional associationsMultivendor systemsTechnical Support Alliance.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>